  "prompt": "What is the difference between adding and committing in Git?",
  "response": "In Git, adding and committing are two fundamental actions in the version control workflow, each serving a distinct purpose in managing changes to a codebase.\n\n1. **git add**:\n   - The `git add` command is used to add changes to the *staging area* (also known as the index). This area acts as an intermediary between your working directory (where you edit files) and the repository's history.\n   - When you modify files in your working directory, those changes aren\u2019t immediately recorded in your Git repository. By using `git add`, you specify which changes you want to include in the next commit.\n   - You can add specific files (`git add filename`), directories (`git add directory_name`), or all changed files (`git add .`) to the staging area.\n   - It\u2019s worth noting that `git add` does not save any snapshots to the repository. It merely prepares the changes for a commit.\n\n2. **git commit**:\n   - The `git commit` command takes the changes that have been staged with `git add` and records them permanently in the Git repository's history.\n   - Committing creates a new commit object in the repository\u2019s history, capturing a snapshot of the project's current state. This includes metadata such as the author, date, and a commit message describing the changes.\n   - It\u2019s a best practice to write clear and descriptive commit messages to make the history of changes easy to understand.\n   - A commit represents a complete and stable version of the project at a given point in time, which you can later revert to if needed.\n\nIn summary, `git add` is about preparing changes while `git commit` is about recording those changes in the repository's history. Together, they allow you to carefully control and document the changes you make within your project.",
